description:
This is part of a sound set i've done in 2002 during a session testing Deconstructor from Tobybear, the basic version
was a simple drum-loop, sliced and processed with pitchshifting, panning, tremolo, delay, reverb, vocoder.. and all those cool onboard fx
Tweaking here and there the original sound was completely mangled..
i saved the work in 2 folders: 'deconstruction-set' contain the longer slices (meant to be used with a sampler), 'deconstruction-kit' collects the smallest slices (to be used in a drum machine)
name: deconstruction-set_opened.wav
tags: off button transform cyborg electro hi-tech mutate processing robot soundesign switch alien clack click noise digital effect fx glitch soundeffect slices cuts

contributors_browser: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1; WOW64; rv:38.0) Gecko/20100101 Firefox/38.0
description:
This is part of a sound kit i've done in 2002 during a session testing Deconstructor from Tobybear, the basic version
was a simple drum-loop, sliced and processed with pitchshifting, panning, tremolo, delay, reverb, vocoder.. and all those cool onboard fx
Tweaking here and there the original sound was completely mangled..
i saved the work in 2 folders: 'deconstruction-set' contain the longer slices (meant to be used with a sampler), 'deconstruction-kit' collects the smallest slices (to be used in a drum machine)
name: deconstruction-kit_kick-it02.wav
tags: cuts digital drum-kit fx glitch noise slices soundeffect

description:
This is part of a sound kit i've done in 2002 during a session testing Deconstructor from Tobybear, the basic version
was a simple drum-loop, sliced and processed with pitchshifting, panning, tremolo, delay, reverb, vocoder.. and all those cool onboard fx
Tweaking here and there the original sound was completely mangled..
i saved the work in 2 folders: 'deconstruction-set' contain the longer slices (meant to be used with a sampler), 'deconstruction-kit' collects the smallest slices (to be used in a drum machine)
name: deconstruction-kit_kick-it03.wav
tags: cuts digital drum-kit fx glitch noise slices soundeffect

description:
This is part of a sound kit i've done in 2002 during a session testing Deconstructor from Tobybear, the basic version
was a simple drum-loop, sliced and processed with pitchshifting, panning, tremolo, delay, reverb, vocoder.. and all those cool onboard fx
Tweaking here and there the original sound was completely mangled..
i saved the work in 2 folders: 'deconstruction-set' contain the longer slices (meant to be used with a sampler), 'deconstruction-kit' collects the smallest slices (to be used in a drum machine)
name: deconstruction-kit_snare-triple.wav

description:
This is part of a sound set i've done in 2002 during a session testing Deconstructor from Tobybear, the basic version
was a simple drum-loop, sliced and processed with pitchshifting, panning, tremolo, delay, reverb, vocoder.. and all those cool onboard fx
Tweaking here and there the original sound was completely mangled..
i saved the work in 2 folders: 'deconstruction-set' contain the longer slices (meant to be used with a sampler), 'deconstruction-kit' collects the smallest slices (to be used in a drum machine)
name: deconstruction-set_turn-off.wav
tags: transform button clack click crash meachanical mutate off processing robot soundesign switch alien cyborg electro hi-tech cuts soundeffect digital effect slices fx glitch noise

contributors_browser: Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 6.1) AppleWebKit/537.36 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/42.0.2311.152 Safari/537.36
description: This sound was created with the technique invented and developed in my PhD, called Histogram Mapping Synthesis (HMS). HMS is based on Cellular Automata (CA) which are mathematical/computational models that create moving images. In the context of HMS, these images are analysed by histogram measurements, giving as a result a sequence of histograms. In a nutshell, these histogram sequences are converted into spectrograms which in turn are rendered into sounds. Additional DSP methods were developed to control the CA and the synthesis so as to be able to design and produce sounds in a predictable and controllable manner. For further reading, see: http://cmr.soc.plymouth.ac.uk/publications/11_SERQUERA.pdf
name: HMS_3.wav
tags: algorithmic Dynamical-Systems sound-effects explosion Histogram-Mapping-Synthesis Cellular-Automata synth FFT-Convolution-Filtering electronic
